    "contenu": "Here is the structured content from the document:\n\n---\n\n### RASPBERRY SAUCE\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 12-ounce package frozen whole raspberries (not in syrup), thawed\n- Framboise to taste (optional)\n\n**Instructions:**\n1. In a blender or food processor, puree the raspberries.\n2. Using a fine mesh strainer, strain the raspberry puree over a bowl to remove the seeds.\n3. Whisk in Framboise to taste, if desired.\n4. The sauce can be prepared up to 2 days ahead of time. Cover and refrigerate until ready to use.\n\n---\n\n**Note on Dessert Complements:**\n- Not all cheesecakes have a pastry or graham cracker crust. Some have a simple coating of toasted breadcrumbs. In other words, they are more like a baked cheese pudding. Fresh sheep's milk ricotta is ideal for this dessert, cow's milk ricotta works well, too. Toasted pine nuts may be added to the basic cheesecake mixture just before you fold in the egg whites. — Joyce\n\n**Wine Pairing Advice:**\n- When serving a sweet bubbly, it's crucial not to overwhelm it. Even though the dessert is both subtle and flavorful, maintaining a proper balance of texture and implicit sweetness is essential to highlight the wine without dominating it. Ideal wine choices are based on Pinot Noir, as they have a core of sweet citrus, ripe tree fruit (apples and pears), and nuances of red fruit. The lemon in this dessert asserts the wine's flavors, true while the raspberry sauce makes a delicious match. Berry and citrus combinations are great with virtually all off-dry to sweet sparkling wines. — Evan\n\n---\n\n### RECOMMENDED PRODUCERS\n#### Sparkling Desert Wines\n\n| Everyday         | Premium                    | Splurge               |\n|------------------|----------------------------|-----------------------|\n| Cinzano          | G. H. Mumm                 | Domaine Huet          |\n| (Piedmont, Italy)| (Champagne, France)        | (Loire Valley, France)|\n| Mumm Napa        | La Spinetta                 | Veuve Cli