    "contenu": "# How to Serve and Store Wine at the Right Temperature\n\n**Mark Squires**\n*Wine Writer*\n\n---\n\n**Introduction:**\nNewcomers to wine encounter various \"rules,\" with temperature considerations being some of the most complicated yet important. Temperature significantly influences both the serving and storage of wine, similar to other natural foods. The taste of wine varies at different temperatures, and the temperature also impacts the longevity and shelf-life of the wine.\n\n**Serving Temperatures:**\n- White wines are typically served chilled, ideally between **35°F to 40°F (2°C to 4°C)**.\n- Red wines are generally served at room temperature, around **70°F to 75°F (21°C to 24°C)**.\n\n**Common Issues:**\n- Whites are often served too cold, which can numb the taste buds and make the wine seem flavorless.\n- Reds served too warm can appear overly alcoholic and clumsy.\n\n**Expert Insight:**\nThe traditional advice about serving red wines at room temperature does not consider that modern homes may be warmer than ideal for wine storage, thus potentially harming the wine's storage condition.\n\n**Storage Importance:**\nProper temperature control is crucial for storing wine, as indicated by its influence on the quality and storage practices emphasized by top wine merchants and importers.\n\n---\n\n**About Mark Squires:**\nMark Squires reviews wines for Robert Parker's *Wine Advocate*, focusing on Portugal's dry wines as well as wines from Israel, Greece, Lebanon, Cyprus, Bulgaria, and Romania. In addition, he conducts various activities related to wine including teaching, consulting, and writing articles. He also hosts his own website and manages \"Mark Squires’ Bulletin Board,\" which is among the world's most popular online forums for discussing wine."
